- 'Most recent' refers to the latest release date of the algorithm versions;
- 'Highest performance rankings' are determined by the average execution time, average best solution, and run count;
- 'Across different projects' means the algorithms are evaluated within the context of multiple projects.

- 'Evolutionary' algorithms are a subset of optimization algorithms inspired by natural selection and genetics;
- 'Machine learning' algorithms are a subset of algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data;
- Optimization instances refer to specific runs or executions of algorithms to solve a particular problem.

- 'Completed' status indicates that the optimization instance has finished running;
- 'Execution time' is measured in seconds;
- 'Best solution' refers to the optimal result found during the run.

sql:
SELECT AVG(execution_time) AS average_execution_time, COUNT(instance_id) AS total_failed_instances
FROM optimization_instances
WHERE status = 'failed';

SELECT execution_time, best_solution
FROM optimization_instances
WHERE status = 'failed';

SELECT AVG(execution_time) AS average_execution_time
FROM optimization_instances
WHERE status = 'completed';

SELECT COUNT(instance_id) 
FROM failure_logs 
WHERE error_type = 'runtime';

SELECT COUNT(instance_id) AS num_instances
FROM algorithm_instances
WHERE algorithm_id = 1;

SELECT AVG(execution_time) AS average_execution_time, AVG(best_solution) AS average_best_solution
FROM optimization_instances
WHERE status = 'failed';

SELECT instance_id, execution_time
FROM optimization_instances
WHERE execution_time > (SELECT AVG(execution_time) FROM optimization_instances);

